<TEXT>
now that leona helmsley is a convicted tax 
evader the question arises will the billionaire hotelier 
accustomed to a penthouse apartment and a 28acre country estate go 
to jail 
or will she be sentenced to community service forced to live in 
and manage a city welfare hotel perhaps as a mayoral candidate 
urged friday 
and how much of her money will she have to give up 
the answers lie with us district judge john walker jr who has 
scheduled sentencing for nov 14 
walkers options range from probation and community service to 
prison time and fines that could go as high as 8 million 
mrs helmsley was convicted wednesday of 33 counts of tax evasion 
and related charges that carry three or fiveyear prison terms 
the judge will base his decision in part on a presentencing 
memorandum by prosecutors submitted shortly before sentencing 
outlining the facts of the case and including a recommendation for 
sentence 
the defense also submits a position paper and can provide letters 
from friends and family in support of mrs helmsleys character at 
the time of sentencing she will be given the opportunity to make a 
personal plea for leniency 
so far prosecutors arent saying what their recommendation will 
be us attorney benito romano said after the verdict that it was 
premature to discuss the sentence and he would not speculate on the 
possibility of community service 
but harrison goldin the city comptroller and a democratic 
candidate for mayor wrote to the judge friday and suggested a 
prison term after which mrs helmsley would be remanded under 
house arrest to a new york city welfare hotel she should be 
required to manage the facility as well as live there 
figures from the internal revenue service indicate that a 
majority of criminal tax offenders are sent to prison 
irs spokesman frank keith said there were 2619 convictions in 
1988 for criminal violations of the federal tax law including tax 
evasion fraudulent tax shelters narcoticsrelated offenses and 
false reporting 
of the sentencings last year 1590 tax offenders received prison 
sentences keith said 
a tax trial that walker presided over in 1987 bears striking 
resemblance to mrs helmsleys although the money involved was much 
greater 
the lead defendant schnejer gurary a wealthy garment center 
executive was convicted of similar charges for using phony bills to 
claim 130 million in tax deductions over seven years mrs helmsley 
was found guilty of disguising about 4 million in personal expenses 
as business expenses in three years 
walker sentenced gurary who was 76 at the time to three years 
in prison and fined him 2 million mrs helmsley is 69 
</TEXT>
