the official after congressional supporters ofthe afhgan resistance 
complained to him about a slowdown in the flow of us arms to the 
rebels and questioned why arms were still being sent to antiwestern 
fundamentalist groups 
the official was formerly the agencys national intelligence 
officer for the middle east an analytical job and had little 
experience in the cias operations division responsible for 
purchasing and the shipping the arms the newspaper quoted the 
critics as saying 
the post did not name the official saying that unnamed senior 
cia officials had asked the newspaper to keep his name confidential 
webster still has full confidence in the official and the cia might 
use him in the future to work overseas under state department cover 
the newspaper quoted the senior agency officials as saying 
among the critics questioning the shortage of arms being sent to 
the afghan rebels sens david boren dokla and robert c byrd 
dwva respectively chairmen of the senates intelligence and 
appropriations committees 
sen gordon j humphrey rnh who heads a special senate task 
force on afghanistan told the newspaper that the cia had gone to 
sleep after the last soviet troops left afghanistan last february 
subsequently humphrey said the supply of us arms to the 
rebels declined to half what it was the first half of 1988 at a time 
when the soviet union was airlifting to the kabul government massive 
new arms shipments 
