<TEXT>
all foods containing residues of alar the 
apple preservative that raised a national furor over possible cancer 
risks will be banned as of may 31 1991 the environmental 
protection agency says 
the agency said friday that it saw no significant health risks 
from eating apples or other food treated with alar but the ban is 
designed to end use of the chemical in response to widespread public 
fears about its safety 
uniroyal chemical co the only domestic maker of alar 
voluntarily agreed in june to take the compound off the market 
although its still being exported the company has disputed 
laboratory findings that the chemical may cause cancer 
the epa reiterated that it plans to announce in january a ban on 
the sale and use of alar after it has received the final results of 
several studies on the chemical 
until the ban becomes effective alars use is still allowed on 
apples cherries nectarines peaches pears peanuts grapes 
tomato transplants and ornamentals 
but to discourage its use the epa said it would begin lowering 
the amount of alar residue permitted on domestic and imported apples 
and other fruits nov 30 with a further reduction a year later and 
a total ban effective may 31 1991 
for tomatoes processed tomatoes tomato pomace meat and meat 
byproducts milk and eggs the ban will take effect nov 30 with no 
phasein period 
alar residues also are found in meat milk and eggs because farm 
animals eat fruit treated with the chemical 
the epa estimates that from 5 percent to 15 percent of the us 
apple crop is treated with alar a growth regulator that improves 
the apples appearance and gives it a longer shelf life 
the agency said friday it believes the use of alar on apples 
declined over the summer because of uniroyals decision to stop 
selling the chemical and a recommendation from the apple growers 
trade association to stop using it 
even so the epa said any apples treated with alar this summer 
could fail to meet the new tolerance levels that take effect nov 30 
and thus could be seized by federal agents 
</TEXT>
