<TEXT>
criticisms of us foreign policy made by drug 
czar william j bennett in the draft of his national drug strategy 
have been deleted from the final version an administration source 
says 
the draft of the international section obtained by the 
associated press notes that some andean nations face economic 
instability and political insurgencies that could be made worse by 
us pressure to wipe out drug crops 
in certain areas and circumstances eradication may be the best 
and most costeffective approach to drug crop suppression the 
draft says 
in others it can be selfdefeating driving farmers into the 
ranks of antigovernment insurgency movements or displacing them to 
other areas which cannot be easily reached 
the final version of the strategy to be presented by president 
bush on tuesday wont include these statements the source said 
we thought that would not be an appropriate message to send to 
the international community the source said 
what remains the source said is this statement from the draft 
careful casebycase consideration must be given to eradication 
programs for their potential effect on total country production 
their marginal cost benefit when compared to other counterdrug 
programs in the same country or area and for the political 
consequences of their use 
the source who spoke on condition of anonymity said that 
doesnt cause us any problem because thats something we would do 
anyway you want to look at eradication as a tool not as an end in 
itself 
the peruvian government faces a threat from sendero luminoso 
guerrillas who have virtually taken control of the upper huallaga 
valley the worlds primary cocagrowing region 
the colombian government meanwhile is under attack both by the 
drug traffickers and the m19 guerrilla group 
administration officials have testified before congress that the 
drug traffickers occasionally work with these guerrilla groups to 
protect themselves from the government but such alliances generally 
are those of convenience motivated by geographical proximity and 
joint hostility to the government 
of the three main cocaine producing countries peru colombia 
and bolivia only bolivia faces no immediate threat from a 
guerrilla organization 
the draft also takes issue with us diplomats alleged failure 
to stress the drug issue something congressional critics have been 
concerned about for years 
the draft says that if the united states wants to broaden support 
for its international counterdrug objectives a vigorous 
coordinated public diplomacy program is essential 
the nations programs in this area are overshadowed by the 
absence of importance given the drug issue as a foreign policy 
concern the draft strategy says they remain unconvincing this 
situation is in urgent need of revision 
the draft also called for greater communication with the soviet 
bloc including cuba on the drug issue 
we must be prepared to share our knowledge and our concern with 
the soviet union and eastern european nations and be willing to 
engage them in cooperative counterdrug activities the draft 
strategy says and we should be prepared to take advantage of 
special opportunities provided by other countries with which we may 
have minimal or no diplomatic relationships to control drug 
trafficking 
this could for example include cuba which might effectively 
block rather than facilitate the passage of drugcarrying aircraft 
toward the united states the draft says 
a shortened version of this message remains in the final 
strategy the source said 
catherine shaw a spokeswoman for the state departments office 
of international narcotics matters said the department already has 
begun working more closely with the soviet bloc on the antidrug 
issue 
a letter of agreement with the soviets signed in january by 
thensecretary of state george shultz opens the door for technical 
exchanges shaw said that would mean we could help train 
soviets when they seize drugs to analyze it exchange information 
on cases 
the state department has said it will be willing to work more 
closely with cuba on antidrug measures only after cuba proves its 
interest in cracking down on the trafficking there for example by 
seizing shipments of cocaine headed toward the united states 
</TEXT>
